    <node id="1. Meilyr Rowlands, the Chief Inspector of Schools for Estyn, acknowledges that recent Estyn inspections of local authorities' education services have shown disappointing results. So far in the current cycle, Estyn has conducted nine inspections of local authorities' education services and plans to inspect two more by the end of the academic year. Three out of the nine inspected local authorities were identified as causing concern: Pembrokeshire, Powys, and Wrexham. Meilyr Rowlands also mentions that a common factor in these inspections is secondary schools, suggesting challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole.&#10;2. Janet Finch-Saunders AM inquired about which local authorities have been identified as causing concern and if they have been inspected under the current cycle. Meilyr Rowlands confirms that three secondary schools in Pembrokeshire, Wrexham, and an unspecified third local authority (possibly Torfaen) are in a category indicating cause for concern.&#10;3. Lynne Neagle AM, the Chair of the Children, Young People and Education Committee, does not express a specific opinion on recent Estyn inspections but welcomes Meilyr Rowlands, Jassa Scott, and Claire Morgan from Estyn for the scrutiny session on Estyn's annual report 2018-19." />
