    <node id="1. Pilot scheme of multi-agency approach: Meilyr Rowlands mentions a pilot scheme to support schools that require greater assistance. This approach involves collaboration between different agencies to provide these schools with the necessary resources and help them cope with the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;2. Focused funding allocation: Janet Finch-Saunders suggests directing additional funding towards schools in need, particularly those struggling with the new curriculum. While Meilyr Rowlands believes the required funding might not be enormous, he acknowledges that these schools do require extra financial support to implement the new curriculum effectively.&#10;&#10;3. Utilizing national resources: The national resource being developed by Claire Morgan aims to provide detailed guidance on self-evaluation and improvement for schools, including secondaries, PRUs, and special schools. This resource can help establish a culture of improvement and reflection within these schools, supporting their efforts to adapt to the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;4. Emphasis on reading proficiency: Since Meilyr Rowlands pointed out that reading might require extra attention due to its strong correlation with family and community factors, it is essential to focus on literacy interventions and strategies in these schools to help students improve their reading skills and meet PISA targets.&#10;&#10;5. Monitoring regional consortia improvement: Although Estyn has not directly inspected regional consortia since 2017, Meilyr Rowlands believes they have shown improvement. Strengthening the monitoring and evaluation of these consortia could help ensure that schools in need receive the necessary support to implement the new curriculum successfully.&#10;&#10;By implementing these efforts, schools requiring significant support can improve their ability to cope with the new curriculum and better serve their students, despite forming a smaller cohort within the education system." />
    <node id=". I see the opportunities, but these schools that are doing well are going to go, 'Wow, up there', but schools are there in the bottom layer and one is genuinely concerned about those children in those schools. Isn't that where the focus should be and any additional funding that's allocated? You talked about releasing teachers for training, but perhaps it's in those particular schools that we need to focus.&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I do agree that the best schools will welcome the opportunities and that their standards will improve even more. But then, with regard to the other schools, in a way, there are two very broad categories, which are those that need only a little support just to help them to improve—. And I believe that the new curriculum and the general support that's going to be surrounding that will be the solution for those schools. It's going to be an opportunity for the quality of the teaching and the learning to improve. But you're right to say that there is another smaller cohort that has a much greater need for support, and they're going to find coping with the new curriculum difficult, because they'll also have many other problems. So, I do agree—. And you're not talking about a huge number" />
    <node id="1. Loss of Confidence: When children are introduced to skills development, such as phonics and reading, before they reach the appropriate developmental stage, they may struggle and fail to grasp these concepts. This early failure can lead to a loss of confidence in their abilities and a belief that they cannot succeed in certain areas.&#10;2. Additional Support Needs: As a result of their struggles, these children may require additional support to catch up with their peers. This could include extra tutoring or resources, which might not be readily available or accessible to them.&#10;3. Negative Impressions and Attitudes: Struggling with skills development at an early age can create negative thoughts about their ability in the minds of these children. Over time, this can develop into a fixed mindset, where they believe that they are simply not good at certain things, leading to decreased motivation and engagement in learning.&#10;4. Long-term Academic Struggles: The combined effects of loss of confidence, additional support needs, and negative impressions can lead to long-term academic struggles for these children. They may have difficulty keeping up with their peers in various subjects, which could negatively impact their overall academic performance and prospects.&#10;5. Delayed Development of Higher-Level Skills: Focusing solely on basic literacy skills without addressing foundational gaps can hinder the development of higher-level reading skills, comprehension, and inference abilities. This can limit learners' overall academic success and their preparedness for lifelong learning.&#10;6. Persistent Gender Disparities: There is a specific concern about the impact on boys regarding reading and literacy, as they often remain low in international assessments. Prioritizing literacy and addressing pressing priorities for boys can help narrow this gap and promote gender equity in education." />
    <node id=" if they're introduced to these things too early they don't succeed, they tend to need additional support, and it can give them a negative impression, it can give them negative thoughts about their ability. So, we need to address that, and really it's about—&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Sorry, what sort of age range are we talking about here?&#10;Speaker: Claire Morgan&#10;Content: These would be children from three to five.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Okay.&#10;Speaker: Claire Morgan&#10;Content: So, this is very, very early on.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: And is there something, then, in that—and I don't think there's much we can do about that, but it may be in terms of the way that the schools or the early learning settings address this—you will have children at a very young age that have almost a year's difference in their age group, so they're born just before 1 September or just after 1 September? So, that's a huge gap, isn't it, at that point in their development?&#10;Speaker: Claire Morgan&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM" />
    <node id="The speaker, Meilyr Rowlands, supports a first-hand evidence-based approach to inspecting schools, which involves direct observations of teaching and learning in the classroom. He believes that this method more accurately assesses the quality of education in schools compared to relying solely on comparative attainment data. Moreover, Meilyr Rowlands is happy to continue inspecting schools without overemphasizing data since it creates a high-stakes culture, which he thinks should be avoided. This indicates that he values personal interaction and direct observation in the evaluation of school performance rather than relying on quantitative data alone." />
    <node id=", we look at leadership, we look at all of these things, and we look at it based on first-hand evidence—what we actually see in the classroom. So, we're quite happy to continue to inspect schools, and we in fact support having less emphasis on data because, although data is useful, and we hope that schools will continue to analyse their data and use that data to help them self-improve and self-evaluate, we don't actually need it and it has actually created a bit of a high-stakes culture. So, I think stepping back from that culture is a good idea.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you very much. We've come to the end of our time, so can I thank you all for your attendance? As usual, you'll receive a transcript to check for accuracy following the meeting. But thank you very much again for coming in this morning.&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Diolch yn fawr—thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Item 3, then, is papers to note. Paper to note 1 is a ministerial update on the emotional and mental health of children and young people in" />
    <node id="1. Estyn's inspections generally find that pupils' well-being develops well in independent schools, and they make good progress. The care, support, and guidance provided by these schools are also assessed as good. This evaluation is based on a wide range of aspects, including first-hand evidence from direct observations of teaching and learning in the classroom, as well as evaluating standards, teaching and learning, well-being, care, support, guidance, leadership, and more.&#10;2. Comparative attainment data is not the sole basis for Estyn's inspections and assessments. While PISA scores are one of the measures of educational performance, Estyn's inspections take into account various aspects of school life to form comprehensive evaluations.&#10;3. Inspections consider boarding provision in independent schools where relevant, focusing on its impact on supporting well-being. The Care Inspectorate Wales looks at the residential aspects of care in these cases, while Estyn assesses the educational side of things. Additionally, inspections evaluate linked children's homes, which can be another room in the same house or located a number of miles away.&#10;4. Shortcomings in independent schools have been identified, such as insufficient awareness of guidance and support for referring pupils to child and adolescent mental health services when needed. Estyn aims to address these concerns through their inspection guidance and the development of resources like the one created by Claire Morgan, which focuses on establishing a culture of improvement and reflection within schools.&#10;5. Pupil confidence in their school's ability to help them with their emotional and mental well-being is generally higher in primary schools than secondary schools. Factors contributing to this difference include pupils facing more challenges in adolescence, as well as potential gaps in support during the transition between primary and secondary education." />
    <node id=" pick up on that as well. Just to explain how we work with independent schools, initially, to give the context. So, there are different kinds of independent schools. So, some have boarding provision, and where they have boarding provision, Care Inspectorate Wales would look at the boarding side of it, we'd look at the educational side of it. There are others where they may have a linked children's home, which can be another room in the same house, or it can be a number of miles away, and similarly there CIW would look at the residential aspects of the care and we'd look at the school. So, I think, there's a focus in the independent school standards regulations, which is a minimum that all schools have to meet to maintain a registration. There is a focus in that on how that school looks after and cares for its pupils, and there are focuses on that element of boarding provision where relevant, and the national minimum standards that the care inspectorate look at that have aspects around supporting well-being as well. What we do find in our inspections is that, overall, we generally find that pupils' well-being develops, they make good progress, and that care, support and guidance that schools give is good. What we mean by" />
    <node id=" generally find that pupils' well-being develops, they make good progress, and that care, support and guidance that schools give is good. What we mean by that, really, practically, is that they are developing their resilience and their self-esteem. In special schools, this might mean particularly that those pupils learn to manage their anxieties better so that they improve their behaviour, which may be one of the reasons why they're in that specialist setting. In mainstream independent schools, what we find is that people develop their tenacity, their curiosity for learning—their resilience in that way. But there are shortcomings sometimes. For example, there was one school where we found that they weren't making appropriate referrals to child and adolescent mental health services. So, these schools do operate independently by their nature, and their awareness, perhaps, of some of the guidance and support that is out there—sometimes, maybe, there can be more to be done, and I think we've talked to Welsh Government about that.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: What's Estyn's role in that—to bring that level of awareness to those schools?&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: I think we do through our inspection guidance, and the independent school" />
    <node id="Meilyr Rowlands views the new curriculum as an opportunity to significantly improve the quality of teaching and learning within schools. He believes that school leaders should use additional funding to prepare for the new curriculum by freeing up teachers to think about what it means for their own teaching practices. This process allows teachers to be more creative in their approaches, which can make teaching a more attractive profession and help retain talented educators. Rowlands suggests that schools need time to thoughtfully consider and implement the new curriculum, emphasizing its potential as a catalyst for positive change in education in Wales." />
    <node id=" leader, what would you—&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Oh, if I were a school leader.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Yes. How would you use any additional funding that would flow into the school?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: It's difficult to make that decision, because every school is different. It is important, of course, that leaders do have the power and the ability to make those decisions themselves. But, certainly, in the short term, the type of thing I would have thought would be to prepare for the new curriculum. That means freeing up teachers to think about what the new curriculum means to them. The schools that have been a part of developing the curriculum have been in a fortunate position in that they've had plenty of time to think about this. So, it's now time—and this was the chief message of my annual report this year—for every school in Wales to start to think. Because I think that the new curriculum is truly an opportunity to take a forward step in terms of how we teach and learn within schools. But that means that time is needed for schools to think this through and, in that thinking, to contact the" />
    <node id="1. Estyn ensures that independent schools are aware of appropriate guidance and support through their inspection process and guidance. They inspect various aspects of school life, including care, support, and guidance provided by these schools. In cases where boarding provision is relevant in independent schools, inspections consider its impact on supporting well-being, with Care Inspectorate Wales looking at residential aspects and Estyn assessing the educational side of things. When shortcomings are identified, such as insufficient awareness of guidance for referring pupils to child and adolescent mental health services, Estyn aims to address these concerns through inspection guidance and resources like those created by Claire Morgan." />
    <node id="Yes, there is a correlation between a lack of support at a higher level and difficulties experienced by some authorities in providing quality education. Meilyr Rowlands, the Chief Inspector of Schools for Estyn, mentioned that out of the nine inspected local authorities so far in the current cycle, three have been identified as causing concern: Pembrokeshire, Powys, and Wrexham. He also noted that a common factor in these inspections is secondary schools, suggesting challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole.&#10;&#10;When discussing ERW, one of the regions including south-west and mid Wales, Meilyr Rowlands acknowledged that the lack of support at that level might be the reason why some authorities are suffering difficulties. This is especially relevant for two of the inspected authorities in this region.&#10;&#10;The dispute at higher levels may indirectly affect children by impacting the quality of education provided in these local authorities. The concerns about a lack of local capacity to support schools and the absence of collective capacity centrally contribute to the challenges faced by these authorities." />
    <node id=" like, we were saying consistently that they tended to be too small. What happened in practice was that authorities did come together voluntarily to have joint advisory services. So, you had Cynnal in the north west, you had the Education and School Improvement Service, you had Gwent—so, they naturally did come together in groups, maybe a little bit smaller than the current regions, but they, of their own accord, produced something not very dissimilar to a region.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Siân, did you have a supplementary?&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Yes, just on ERW. Does the fact that there is a dispute on the highest level feed down to the school and to the children? Are the children in south-west and mid Wales affected by this? Are standards decreasing in that part of Wales?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Well, it's difficult to say directly, but we have inspected nine authorities and two of those are in that area, so, the lack of support at that level, as Jassa was saying, may be the reason why those authorities are suffering difficulties.&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;" />
    <node id="The agreed approach for inspecting and reporting on how regional consortia support curriculum reform over the next few years is through a thematic approach. Estyn, the education and training inspectorate for Wales, will look specifically at how each consortium is supporting curriculum reform in their local authorities as part of their local authority inspections. This will be reported on, but it won't be the same as doing an inspection of the consortia's work at this time. Estyn has discussed with the Welsh Government the possibility of adapting inspection to look specifically at regional consortia if they become statutory entities in the future. Estyn is currently negotiating with the Welsh Government to be able to inspect local authorities and regions at the same time, which would allow for a more comprehensive evaluation of the support provided by regional consortia." />
    <node id="&#10;Content: So, what is the cycle of inspections for regional consortia, and how robust are those inspections? What areas do you cover?&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Well, regional consortia aren't actually statutory entities at the moment, and we don't have specific inspection powers relating to regional consortia. What we have are powers to inspect school improvement. So, on each of our local authority inspections, there will be, usually, an area that we're looking at that relates to school improvement, and that would involve us looking at the work of the consortia that the local authority has commissioned. What we've agreed with Welsh Government is that, over the next few years, we will take a thematic approach. So, the first area that we've said is that we'll look specifically at how each of them is supporting curriculum reform, and report on that. So, that will report specifically on the different ones, but it wouldn't be the same as doing an inspection of their work at this time.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Should they be on a statutory footing?&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Well, I think that's something to be discussed" />
    <node id=" evidence of their impact through that—they're not always focused, in those schools causing concern, on improving teaching and learning, so actually getting in and looking and working with teachers and with staff to actually make improvements there. I think, generally, their support for secondary schools has had less impact across the consortia than it has for primary schools, and I think sometimes that's because they're struggling to recruit appropriate specialists, to support with secondary, or perhaps they don't have the depth of strong practice that we talked about earlier within their region. So, they're having to work a bit harder to find effective practice, to share practice and to get the secondary expertise and knowledge to support those schools. We will be, over the next year, looking specifically at the work of consortia to support curriculum reform work. Well, we think we will be—we haven’t had our remit letter yet. But that's one of the areas we've discussed, about doing some specific work on over the next year to look in a bit more depth.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: So, what is the cycle of inspections for regional consortia, and how robust are those inspections? What areas do you cover?&#10;Spe" />
    <node id="&#10;Content: Should they be on a statutory footing?&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Well, I think that's something to be discussed over the next few years. There's, obviously, local government legislation that has been debated recently, which has the potential to create corporate joint committees, and school improvement was one of the areas that is being considered there. So, there may be an opportunity, if that's created, to think how we then adapt inspection to look specifically at that. So, I think there is an opportunity. I think we do get a handle on their work through the local authority and, ultimately, it's looking at what that consortia brings to that local authority and to the schools and the pupils in that area that's the important bit, I think, ultimately, to see the impact there. So, we are looking at them in that way, and then taking that thematic approach, but we'll keep reviewing it over the next couple of years.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. And what are Estyn's views on the latest position regarding regional working in south-west and mid Wales? Would it be preferable for school improvement advisers to be based in the consortium, Education" />
    <node id="1. A visit is planned to all authorities under ERW's jurisdiction, including regions in south-west and mid Wales, to assess their school improvement services. This visit aims to ensure that appropriate plans are in place for school improvement services and to survey schools about the support they receive from their authority or central teams in ERW.&#10;   &#10;2. The purpose of this visit is to gauge any potential disadvantages or impacts on schools firsthand, as well as to make sure that ERW has a plan for an appropriate school improvement service going forward. This proactive measure will help identify areas where support is needed and allow for the implementation of measures to improve educational quality.&#10;&#10;3. There is a joint committee meeting scheduled for March 19th, after which more information is expected regarding ERW's plans to manage their collective set of services. Stakeholders hope to gain clarity on how ERW will proceed in managing and delivering school improvement services to address the current concerns and challenges.&#10;&#10;4. A detailed link visit will be conducted to understand how ERW authorities are mitigating risks arising from recent developments, such as staff departures and lack of support at higher levels. This follow-up visit will help evaluate the effectiveness of existing measures and identify areas for improvement in school improvement services." />
    <node id="1. Regional Consortia Inspections: The cycle of inspections for regional consortia is not explicitly mentioned in the transcripts; however, it is stated that the work of consortia regarding supporting curriculum reform will be looked at specifically over the next year. The robustness of these inspections and their coverage areas are also not detailed.&#10;&#10;2. Support from External Agencies: Over the past three years, external agencies have generally improved in their support for schools causing concern, particularly in terms of literacy and numeracy. Schools' knowledge of individual institutions' strengths and weaknesses has been utilized better to support and challenge these schools. However, there is still room for improvement in supporting schools in developing digital competence.&#10;&#10;3. Support for Literacy: Literacy remains a top priority for Estyn, and it has seen improvements over the years due to consistent prioritization. However, there are still concerns about boys' reading and literacy skills, with Wales consistently ranking low in Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA) ratings for reading.&#10;&#10;4. Challenges in Secondary Schools: There is a common factor of secondary schools struggling in inspections across several local authorities, which suggests challenges in this area for both individual authorities and the education system as a whole. Two inspected authorities in ERW's region (South-west and Mid Wales) might be experiencing difficulties due to a lack of support at that level.&#10;&#10;5. Impact on Quality of Education: The dispute at higher levels may indirectly affect children by impacting the quality of education provided in local authorities. Concerns about a lack of local capacity to support schools and the absence of collective capacity centrally contribute to the challenges faced by these authorities." />
    <node id=" that are in need of special measures take just over two years, on average. Some are shorter; some are quite a considerable amount longer. It's a little less for schools that go into significant improvement. With primary schools, of course, it's much shorter because the issues are far less complex; it's easier to bring about improvements in teaching. When you've got large numbers of staff, you've got large secondary schools, it takes time to actually bring about those improvements, but it is a long time, just over two years, when you think that some pupils, maybe in key stage 4 for the two years—. Certainly, we want to see schools coming out of category much quicker, and this is where the multi-agency approach certainly is a positive step. All partners involved in supporting the school are involved in these improvement boards. They focus on bringing about improvement in the areas of the school that are weakest, and it is the responsibility of everybody involved—that is: ourselves, the regions, local authorities, the schools themselves and their governing bodies—to look at how they can best support the school to bring about that improvement. So, it's getting an agreement on what the issues are, and then planning the support so that we avoid duplication, but that we" />
    <node id="Meilyr Rowlands expresses concern about the current situation regarding secondary schools in Wales, acknowledging that there are challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole. He is worried that half of Welsh children face uncertain prospects of attending a good or better secondary school, with over 10% of schools failing and 12% under Estyn review.&#10;&#10;However, Meilyr Rowlands also highlights positive aspects of the education system in Wales, mentioning the primary sector, special sector, and post-16 as sectors that are doing well. He sees the new curriculum as an opportunity to significantly improve the quality of teaching and learning within schools, believing that school leaders should use additional funding to prepare for the new curriculum by freeing up teachers to think about what it means for their own teaching practices.&#10;&#10;In summary, Meilyr Rowlands is both concerned about the current state of secondary education in Wales and appreciative of the positive aspects found in other sectors of the Welsh education system." />
    <node id="1. Pupil Development and Reflectiveness: As pupils grow older, particularly during their teenage years in secondary school, they face more challenges and become more reflective and discerning. They may notice differences between their everyday life experiences at school and the messages they receive about well-being from lessons, assemblies, and school policies. This increased discernment can lead to a lower perception of well-being in secondary school compared to primary school.&#10;   &#10;2. Transition and Support Structure: In primary schools, pupils typically have a go-to adult, usually their teacher, for support. However, secondary schools need to find ways to ensure that pupils still feel supported, even though the structure is different and there are more students. This can be more challenging in secondary schools, but successful ones manage to create an environment where pupils feel they have trusted adults who care about them.&#10;&#10;3. Personal and Social Education: There are concerns about the effectiveness of personal and social education, as well as health and well-being support in both primary and secondary schools. This can contribute to pupils' lower perception of well-being, especially if they do not feel that their school is adequately addressing these aspects.&#10;&#10;4. Curriculum Changes: The new curriculum gives schools more scope to tailor teaching and learning to specific groups, including more able, advantaged, or disadvantaged students. However, the successful implementation of this new curriculum can be impacted by factors such as budget constraints, staffing issues, and teacher shortages, particularly in secondary schools and in specific subjects.&#10;&#10;5. Emotional and Mental Well-being Support: Pupil confidence in their school's ability to help them with emotional and mental well-being is generally higher in primary schools than secondary schools. This could be due to the challenges faced during adolescence, as well as potential gaps in support during the transition from primary to secondary education." />
    <node id=", as you say. And I think there are a number of factors that we think contribute to that: I think one of the factors is that pupils face, sometimes, more challenges as they get older in those teenage years, but they also become more reflective and perhaps more discerning. And I think what we find in secondary schools is perhaps secondary school pupils notice sometimes the differences between their everyday life that they experience in school and perhaps the messages that they're getting about well-being in terms of their lessons, in terms of assemblies and in terms of school policies and so on. So, they are probably more discerning in noticing those differences and maybe there are some of those differences also there in primary school, but the pupils don't notice. I think we've already touched upon things like the differences in the way that, at primary school, you would tend to have a go-to adult, which is your teacher. The best secondary schools find ways to make sure that pupils do feel that level of support and feel there are trusted people, but it's more of a challenge to make sure that that happens, because of the way they're operating. We still have some concerns about personal and social education and the health and well-being support, which we've made a recommendation" />
    <node id="1. Risk of destabilization: Neath Port Talbot's withdrawal from ERW has the potential to cause a ripple effect, leading to instability across the entire national model for school improvement. This could negatively impact the Welsh Government's reliance on regional consortia to support curriculum reform and drive professional learning.&#10;&#10;2. Reduced capacity: The withdrawal of Neath Port Talbot from ERW may lead to reduced capacity within the consortium, affecting its ability to deliver school improvement services effectively across the region. This could exacerbate existing challenges faced by local authorities in providing quality education, as support at a higher level is already lacking.&#10;&#10;3. Delayed curriculum reform: The potential instability caused by Neath Port Talbot's withdrawal might hinder the progress of curriculum reform efforts, as regional consortia play a crucial role in supporting these changes at the local level. This could result in delays or disruptions to the implementation of new curricula and related initiatives.&#10;&#10;4. Inefficient resource allocation: The withdrawal may lead to inefficient use of resources, both financial and human, as ERW would need to adjust its plans and strategies to account for the loss of Neath Port Talbot's contribution. This could result in a misallocation of resources, potentially diverting funds away from school improvement initiatives and towards administrative tasks.&#10;&#10;5. Impact on regional collaboration: A withdrawal from ERW by Neath Port Talbot could set a precedent for other local authorities to follow suit, potentially undermining the regional collaboration that has been established through the consortium model. This could weaken the collective capacity of regional consortia to address shared challenges and leverage economies of scale in delivering school improvement services.&#10;&#10;6. Slower progress on educational quality: Ultimately, the potential instability, reduced capacity, and disrupted collaboration resulting from Neath Port Talbot's withdrawal could slow down progress towards improving educational quality across Wales. This could have long-term consequences for schools, learners, and the wider community, highlighting the importance of maintaining a stable and effective national school improvement model." />
    <node id=" Neath Port Talbot's intention to withdraw from regional working via ERW?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I think we've talked in general terms and we feel that local authorities probably are too small on their own. In general terms, you can't say that any particular authority couldn't, maybe, put things together in such a way that it's effective. Also, it has a knock-on effect on the rest of the consortium, if one withdraws. I don't know whether, Jassa, you've got anything to add to the general points we've made.&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: I mean, I think, what you've alluded to there, it has the potential to be a destabilising factor across the whole of the national model that we've got for supporting school improvement at a time where Welsh Government are kind of relying heavily on that consortium model to help support curriculum reform and to drive professional learning and be the conduit for lots of the aspects of reform that we've talked about. So, I think that potential risk of any destabilising across the system is a disadvantage generally. I think—. Clearly, we've talked about that capacity at a local level. There is that aspect of" />
    <node id="Based on the provided transcripts, there has been an improvement in the support from external agencies, including education inspectors, over the past three years. However, their support for developing digital competence in schools has been identified as a weaker area, even though it is a priority in the early stages of curriculum developments.&#10;&#10;Regarding schools causing concern, there is still room for improvement in focusing on teaching and learning. Inspectors have noticed that not all schools causing concern are consistently focused on improving teaching and learning, which is crucial for making improvements. This issue has been observed during local authority inspections, providing first-hand evidence of the impact of inspectors' support.&#10;&#10;In summary, while education inspectors have generally improved their support for schools in recent years, there is still a need to strengthen their focus on digital competence and consistently prioritize teaching and learning in schools causing concern." />
    <node id="Yes, there is evidence that voluntary associations like Cynnal, Education and School Improvement Service, and Gwent have formed groups that resemble a region, similar to the current regional consortia. These associations were formed by smaller authorities coming together voluntarily to create joint advisory services.&#10;&#10;The transcript also suggests that the lack of support at a higher level may be contributing to difficulties in certain authorities within south-west and mid Wales, which could potentially impact standards for children in those areas. Meilyr Rowlands mentioned that two out of the nine inspected authorities are in this region, and the absence of support at that level might be the reason why these authorities are facing challenges. This ongoing dispute and reorganization discussions may take energy away from investing in improving schools and supporting staff in those areas." />
    <node id="Yes, Meilyr Rowlands' confidence that standards won't slip during the period of preparation for major educational reforms could be based on small incremental improvements seen across all education levels, including primary schools where the new curriculum ethos has already been articulated through the foundation phase. He emphasizes that any kind of major educational reform comes with risks, but he believes there is a track record of standards and provision not slipping in recent years. This confidence might be further bolstered by the fact that primary schools have shown improvements, providing evidence that the new curriculum ethos can be successfully implemented." />
    <node id=", from the point of view of scrutiny, will we be back in a situation where we're being told, 'You can't compare one set of results against the previous year's results, because of the nature of the change'?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Bore da, bawb. Thank you for the invitation to come here. I think that's a good question. I think any kind of major educational reform has got risks attached to it, particularly if those changes were made too quickly. I think this process of reform has been going on in the background for a few years now, so I think there is a track record of standards and provision not slipping. We've seen small incremental improvements. So, overall, I think we can be fairly confident that standards won't slip during this period of preparation.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Can I just ask: is that based on your evidence around primary schools, where the sort of ethos that we've seen in the curriculum has been already articulated through the foundation phase?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: The track record I'm talking about is across the board, so it's very difficult to think of anything that's actually got worse over the" />
    <node id="1. Age Differences in Early Learning Settings: Children aged three to five can have up to a year's difference in age, which can lead to significant developmental gaps at this stage. These differences may make it challenging for some children to grasp certain skills, such as phonics and reading, when introduced too early. This can result in a loss of confidence, negative impressions about their abilities, and the need for additional support.&#10;2. Addressing Age Differences: Early learning settings and schools can address this issue by considering age differences among children and tailoring skill development accordingly. By introducing skills like phonics and reading at appropriate developmental stages, educators can help prevent early failure, loss of confidence, and negative impressions about abilities.&#10;3. Importance of Foundational Literacy Skills: It is crucial to develop foundational literacy skills among children aged three to five, as these skills serve as the basis for higher-level reading skills, comprehension, and inference abilities. Prioritizing literacy and addressing pressing priorities for boys can help narrow gender gaps and promote equity in education.&#10;4. Role of Education Inspectors: While education inspectors have generally improved their support for schools in recent years, they should continue to focus on strengthening digital competence and consistently prioritizing teaching and learning in schools causing concern. This can help ensure that all children, regardless of age differences, receive the necessary support and guidance to succeed in early learning settings." />
    <node id="1. Advocate for increased education funding: Lobbying the government for greater overall funding for education is crucial to ensure that schools have the resources they need to implement the new curriculum and support essential services like well-being, attendance promotion, and behavior support.&#10;2. Allocate funds specifically for local authority services: When distributing education funds, allocate a portion of it to local authority services to ensure they have the necessary resources to support schools and students effectively.&#10;3. Encourage efficient use of existing resources: Promote best practices in resource management among schools and local authorities to maximize the impact of available funding. This could include sharing resources, collaborating on projects, or implementing cost-saving measures.&#10;4. Monitor funding distribution and its impact: Regularly assess how funds are being distributed among schools and local authority services, ensuring that the allocation is equitable and effective in supporting the new curriculum's implementation and student success.&#10;5. Establish partnerships with community organizations: Collaborate with community organizations to leverage additional resources and support for schools and students. This could include volunteering programs, mentorship opportunities, or donations of materials and equipment.&#10;6. Encourage schools to engage their communities in the funding process: Empower schools to involve local communities in fundraising efforts and decision-making around resource allocation, helping to build a broader base of support for education and ensuring that funds are used in ways that align with community values and priorities." />
    <node id=" terms of how we teach and learn within schools. But that means that time is needed for schools to think this through and, in that thinking, to contact the community, to talk to their children as well, to see what the community in its broader sense would like to see being in the new curriculum, because it's up to every school. Although the new curriculum sets a framework, it is up to each and every school to decide what they're going to teach, and what they're teaching in order to prepare their young people for this new world that we have in the twenty-first century. Therefore, to give you a somewhat superficial answer, I would be setting time aside for the training of teachers.&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Can I just add one thing there? I think what we've seen over the years recently is that local authorities, to some extent, have safeguarded the funding that goes to the schools, but the effect of that is that we've seen less funding going into some of the local authority services; for example, those services that support well-being, that promote attendance, and that perhaps support behaviour and assistance for schools. So, I think that all of those factors contribute to how schools can support and assist their pupils" />
