    <edge source=" secondary is a recognition of that difference. In terms of funding, probably everyone in this room, and certainly me included, would like to see more money for the education system—any educationalist would like to see that. But, you know, that is a decision for local and central Government to decide how much they can afford. I think there is an argument for saying that the funding has become more challenging for schools over time.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Can I ask, just to keep it on track, are you finding that that's having an impact on secondary schools particularly—their ability to make space to get their heads around the curriculum?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I don't think you can make that straightforward correlation. But if you do look at surpluses and reserves, they have been more or less constant for primary schools over a long period of time, but they have declined for secondary schools. So, I think there probably is an argument for saying that we need to look at the funding of secondary schools in particular because, overall, they're in deficit now. So, I think there is an argument for looking at that. The other thing that's worth saying about funding is that even a small" target="The puzzle of the unclosed achievement gap between disadvantaged students and their peers after a £475 million investment over ten years in the pupil deprivation grant could be attributed to several factors. Meilyr Rowlands, in the discussion, points out that poverty is a complex social phenomenon that schools cannot solve independently, hinting at some of the challenges lying beyond school influence.&#10;&#10;It is mentioned that compared to other countries, Wales performs relatively well in terms of educational equity according to PISA assessments. However, the widening issues of poverty and austerity may be contributing to the stagnant progress in narrowing the achievement gap within Wales itself. In essence, schools are running hard just to stay still amidst these growing societal challenges.&#10;&#10;Moreover, Meilyr Rowlands highlights that improving teaching and learning quality can disproportionately benefit disadvantaged students, emphasizing that the new curriculum focuses on enhancing classroom instruction quality. Therefore, investing in better teaching practices could be a crucial strategy to impact the achievement gap.&#10;&#10;Despite primary schools maintaining more consistent surplus funds, secondary schools face declining reserves and increasing deficits, which impacts their ability to prepare for changes such as the new curriculum and retain adequate staffing levels. It is also noted that there may not be a straightforward correlation between school funding challenges and readiness for curriculum implementation; however, it does introduce difficulties for secondary schools' overall capacity to operate effectively.&#10;&#10;Furthermore, Lynne Neagle AM raises concerns about children from better-off backgrounds in Wales underperforming compared to their peers in the rest of the United Kingdom, which adds another dimension to educational disparities and governmental funding decisions in Wales. The challenge for policymakers lies in addressing these complex socioeconomic factors that influence student achievement while ensuring schools receive adequate resources to tackle these issues head-on.">
