    <edge source="The requirement for continuous professional development (CPD) in preparation for the new curriculum is expected to have a positive impact on the ability of secondary schools to implement it. According to Meilyr Rowlands, the new curriculum gives back agency and ownership to teachers, making teaching a more creative profession. This increased creativity and autonomy in the teaching process can make teaching an attractive profession for intelligent people.&#10;&#10;However, there are short-term challenges. The CPD requirements will be implemented alongside existing pressures on teachers' time, which may affect their ability to fully engage with the new curriculum. Nonetheless, Meilyr Rowlands believes that the new curriculum will have a positive impact on teacher morale and attractiveness of the profession in the long run.&#10;&#10;In summary, while the CPD requirements might place additional demands on secondary school teachers, they are also expected to make teaching more attractive and re-professionalize the profession, which is crucial for effective implementation of the new curriculum." target="1. Advocate for increased education funding: Lobbying the government for greater overall funding for education is crucial to ensure that schools have the resources they need to implement the new curriculum and support essential services like well-being, attendance promotion, and behavior support.&#10;2. Allocate funds specifically for local authority services: When distributing education funds, allocate a portion of it to local authority services to ensure they have the necessary resources to support schools and students effectively.&#10;3. Encourage efficient use of existing resources: Promote best practices in resource management among schools and local authorities to maximize the impact of available funding. This could include sharing resources, collaborating on projects, or implementing cost-saving measures.&#10;4. Monitor funding distribution and its impact: Regularly assess how funds are being distributed among schools and local authority services, ensuring that the allocation is equitable and effective in supporting the new curriculum's implementation and student success.&#10;5. Establish partnerships with community organizations: Collaborate with community organizations to leverage additional resources and support for schools and students. This could include volunteering programs, mentorship opportunities, or donations of materials and equipment.&#10;6. Encourage schools to engage their communities in the funding process: Empower schools to involve local communities in fundraising efforts and decision-making around resource allocation, helping to build a broader base of support for education and ensuring that funds are used in ways that align with community values and priorities.">
