    <edge source="The national resource being developed by Claire Morgan is intended to provide schools with detailed guidance on how they can approach not only self-evaluation but also bring about improvement. This resource is seen as having the potential to support schools in developing a culture that focuses on improvement and reflection, involving all staff in the development process. The resource is currently in the pilot stage, involving around 40 schools, with half of them involved in developing the tools and approaches from the start and 22 new schools joining this year. It will include various tools and approaches that schools can use to improve the quality of self-evaluation throughout the school, including primaries, secondaries, PRUs, and special schools. The ultimate goal is to establish a culture within the school that focuses on improvement and reflection, with all staff involved in development." target="1. Pilot scheme of multi-agency approach: Meilyr Rowlands mentions a pilot scheme to support schools that require greater assistance. This approach involves collaboration between different agencies to provide these schools with the necessary resources and help them cope with the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;2. Focused funding allocation: Janet Finch-Saunders suggests directing additional funding towards schools in need, particularly those struggling with the new curriculum. While Meilyr Rowlands believes the required funding might not be enormous, he acknowledges that these schools do require extra financial support to implement the new curriculum effectively.&#10;&#10;3. Utilizing national resources: The national resource being developed by Claire Morgan aims to provide detailed guidance on self-evaluation and improvement for schools, including secondaries, PRUs, and special schools. This resource can help establish a culture of improvement and reflection within these schools, supporting their efforts to adapt to the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;4. Emphasis 