    <edge source="The national resource being developed by Claire Morgan is intended to provide schools with detailed guidance on how they can approach not only self-evaluation but also bring about improvement. This resource is seen as having the potential to support schools in developing a culture that focuses on improvement and reflection, involving all staff in the development process. The resource is currently in the pilot stage, involving around 40 schools, with half of them involved in developing the tools and approaches from the start and 22 new schools joining this year. It will include various tools and approaches that schools can use to improve the quality of self-evaluation throughout the school, including primaries, secondaries, PRUs, and special schools. The ultimate goal is to establish a culture within the school that focuses on improvement and reflection, with all staff involved in development." target="1. Regional Consortia Inspections: The cycle of inspections for regional consortia is not explicitly mentioned in the transcripts; however, it is stated that the work of consortia regarding supporting curriculum reform will be looked at specifically over the next year. The robustness of these inspections and their coverage areas are also not detailed.&#10;&#10;2. Support from External Agencies: Over the past three years, external agencies have generally improved in their support for schools causing concern, particularly in terms of literacy and numeracy. Schools' knowledge of individual institutions' strengths and weaknesses has been utilized better to support and challenge these schools. However, there is still room for improvement in supporting schools in developing digital competence.&#10;&#10;3. Support for Literacy: Literacy remains a top priority for Estyn, and it has seen improvements over the years due to consistent prioritization. However, there are still concerns about boys' reading and literacy skills, with Wales consistently ranking low in