    <edge source="The concerns regarding ERW (Education through Regional Working) stem from the region's progress, or lack thereof, particularly in light of recent developments. These developments include the resignation of the chair of the joint committee, the appointment of a temporary managing director without clear plans for permanency, leadership team members leaving resulting in reduced capacity, and the departure of various staff appointed just last summer.&#10;&#10;Additionally, ERW's budget has not been agreed upon, and key meetings such as executive board and joint committee meetings have been cancelled. These issues have led to significant worries about ERW, prompting plans for a visit next month to all authorities under ERW's jurisdiction. This visit aims to ensure that appropriate school improvement services are in place and to survey schools in the region about the support they receive from their authority or central teams in ERW. The goal is to gauge any potential disadvantages or impacts on schools firsthand.&#10;&#10;There also seems to be a lack of clarity regarding how ERW plans to manage their collective set of services going forward, with a joint committee meeting scheduled for March 19th, after which more information is expected." target=" said, currently, what we intend to do in the short is to do some thematic work on that. In terms of ERW, they were the region that, at the end of the last cycle of regional inspections, we were still monitoring. We are concerned about their progress, particularly in the light of recent developments. So, for example, the chair of the joint committee has resigned, the managing director remains a temporary appointment and there are no clear plans for a permanent leadership. Some of the leadership team have left—the capacity has gone down—and various staff that were appointed last summer have already left. The budget has not been agreed and certain key meetings—executive board and joint committee meetings—have been cancelled. So, we are particularly worried about ERW, and, because of that, we will be going in to visit them in April—next month—and we'll be visiting all of the authorities to make sure that they do have a plan for an appropriate school improvement service going forward. But, Jassa, probably, can say a little bit more about our plans there.&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Yes, I think you asked a specific question about, you know, which is better. I think our view has">
