    <edge source=" said, currently, what we intend to do in the short is to do some thematic work on that. In terms of ERW, they were the region that, at the end of the last cycle of regional inspections, we were still monitoring. We are concerned about their progress, particularly in the light of recent developments. So, for example, the chair of the joint committee has resigned, the managing director remains a temporary appointment and there are no clear plans for a permanent leadership. Some of the leadership team have left—the capacity has gone down—and various staff that were appointed last summer have already left. The budget has not been agreed and certain key meetings—executive board and joint committee meetings—have been cancelled. So, we are particularly worried about ERW, and, because of that, we will be going in to visit them in April—next month—and we'll be visiting all of the authorities to make sure that they do have a plan for an appropriate school improvement service going forward. But, Jassa, probably, can say a little bit more about our plans there.&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Yes, I think you asked a specific question about, you know, which is better. I think our view has" target="1. A visit is planned to all authorities under ERW's jurisdiction, including regions in south-west and mid Wales, to assess their school improvement services. This visit aims to ensure that appropriate plans are in place for school improvement services and to survey schools about the support they receive from their authority or central teams in ERW.&#10;   &#10;2. The purpose of this visit is to gauge any potential disadvantages or impacts on schools firsthand, as well as to make sure that ERW has a plan for an appropriate school improvement service going forward. This proactive measure will help identify areas where support is needed and allow for the implementation of measures to improve educational quality.&#10;&#10;3. There is a joint committee meeting scheduled for March 19th, after which more information is expected regarding ERW's plans to manage their collective set of services. Stakeholders hope to gain clarity on how ERW will proceed in managing and delivering school improvement services to address the current concerns and challenges.&#10;&#10;4. A detailed link visit will be conducted to understand how ERW authorities are mitigating risks arising from recent developments, such as staff departures and lack of support at higher levels. This follow-up visit will help evaluate the effectiveness of existing measures and identify areas for improvement in school improvement services.">
