    <edge source="1. Estyn's inspection process draws conclusions and assesses standards in schools by considering a wide range of aspects, including first-hand evidence from direct observations of teaching and learning in the classroom, as well as evaluating standards, teaching and learning, well-being, care, support, guidance, leadership, and more.&#10;2. Comparative attainment data is not the sole basis for Estyn's inspections and assessments, as there was a misconception that such data was only used for inspection purposes.&#10;3. While PISA scores are one of the measures of educational performance, Estyn's inspections take into account various aspects of school life to form comprehensive evaluations." target="The speaker, Meilyr Rowlands, supports a first-hand evidence-based approach to inspecting schools, which involves direct observations of teaching and learning in the classroom. He believes that this method more accurately assesses the quality of education in schools compared to relying solely on comparative attainment data. Moreover, Meilyr Rowlands is happy to continue inspecting schools without overemphasizing data since it creates a high-stakes culture, which he thinks should be avoided. This indicates that he values personal interaction and direct observation in the evaluation of school performance rather than relying on quantitative data alone.">
