    <edge source=". I see the opportunities, but these schools that are doing well are going to go, 'Wow, up there', but schools are there in the bottom layer and one is genuinely concerned about those children in those schools. Isn't that where the focus should be and any additional funding that's allocated? You talked about releasing teachers for training, but perhaps it's in those particular schools that we need to focus.&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I do agree that the best schools will welcome the opportunities and that their standards will improve even more. But then, with regard to the other schools, in a way, there are two very broad categories, which are those that need only a little support just to help them to improve—. And I believe that the new curriculum and the general support that's going to be surrounding that will be the solution for those schools. It's going to be an opportunity for the quality of the teaching and the learning to improve. But you're right to say that there is another smaller cohort that has a much greater need for support, and they're going to find coping with the new curriculum difficult, because they'll also have many other problems. So, I do agree—. And you're not talking about a huge number" target="Yes, Meilyr Rowlands' confidence that standards won't slip during the period of preparation for major educational reforms could be based on small incremental improvements seen across all education levels, including primary schools where the new curriculum ethos has already been articulated through the foundation phase. He emphasizes that any kind of major educational reform comes with risks, but he believes there is a track record of standards and provision not slipping in recent years. This confidence might be further bolstered by the fact that primary schools have shown improvements, providing evidence that the new curriculum ethos can be successfully implemented.">
