    <edge source="1. Loss of Confidence: When children are introduced to skills development, such as phonics and reading, before they reach the appropriate developmental stage, they may struggle and fail to grasp these concepts. This early failure can lead to a loss of confidence in their abilities and a belief that they cannot succeed in certain areas.&#10;2. Additional Support Needs: As a result of their struggles, these children may require additional support to catch up with their peers. This could include extra tutoring or resources, which might not be readily available or accessible to them.&#10;3. Negative Impressions and Attitudes: Struggling with skills development at an early age can create negative thoughts about their ability in the minds of these children. Over time, this can develop into a fixed mindset, where they believe that they are simply not good at certain things, leading to decreased motivation and engagement in learning.&#10;4. Long-term Academic Struggles: The combined effects of loss of confidence, additional support needs, and negative impressions can lead to long-term academic struggles for these children. They may have difficulty keeping up with their peers in various subjects, which could negatively impact their overall academic performance and prospects.&#10;5. Delayed Development of Higher-Level Skills: Focusing solely on basic literacy skills without addressing foundational gaps can hinder the development of higher-level reading skills, comprehension, and inference abilities. This can limit learners' overall academic success and their preparedness for lifelong learning.&#10;6. Persistent Gender Disparities: There is a specific concern about the impact on boys regarding reading and literacy, as they often remain low in international assessments. Prioritizing literacy and addressing pressing priorities for boys can help narrow this gap and promote gender equity in education." target=" if they're introduced to these things too early they don't succeed, they tend to need additional support, and it can give them a negative impression, it can give them negative thoughts about their ability. So, we need to address that, and really it's about—&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Sorry, what sort of age range are we talking about here?&#10;Speaker: Claire Morgan&#10;Content: These would be children from three to five.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Okay.&#10;Speaker: Claire Morgan&#10;Content: So, this is very, very early on.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: And is there something, then, in that—and I don't think there's much we can do about that, but it may be in terms of the way that the schools or the early learning settings address this—you will have children at a very young age that have almost a year's difference in their age group, so they're born just before 1 September or just after 1 September? So, that's a huge gap, isn't it, at that point in their development?&#10;Speaker: Claire Morgan&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM">
