    <edge source="The speaker, Meilyr Rowlands, supports a first-hand evidence-based approach to inspecting schools, which involves direct observations of teaching and learning in the classroom. He believes that this method more accurately assesses the quality of education in schools compared to relying solely on comparative attainment data. Moreover, Meilyr Rowlands is happy to continue inspecting schools without overemphasizing data since it creates a high-stakes culture, which he thinks should be avoided. This indicates that he values personal interaction and direct observation in the evaluation of school performance rather than relying on quantitative data alone." target="Meilyr Rowlands views the new curriculum as an opportunity to significantly improve the quality of teaching and learning within schools. He believes that school leaders should use additional funding to prepare for the new curriculum by freeing up teachers to think about what it means for their own teaching practices. This process allows teachers to be more creative in their approaches, which can make teaching a more attractive profession and help retain talented educators. Rowlands suggests that schools need time to thoughtfully consider and implement the new curriculum, emphasizing its potential as a catalyst for positive change in education in Wales.">
