    <edge source="1. Estyn's inspections generally find that pupils' well-being develops well in independent schools, and they make good progress. The care, support, and guidance provided by these schools are also assessed as good. This evaluation is based on a wide range of aspects, including first-hand evidence from direct observations of teaching and learning in the classroom, as well as evaluating standards, teaching and learning, well-being, care, support, guidance, leadership, and more.&#10;2. Comparative attainment data is not the sole basis for Estyn's inspections and assessments. While PISA scores are one of the measures of educational performance, Estyn's inspections take into account various aspects of school life to form comprehensive evaluations.&#10;3. Inspections consider boarding provision in independent schools where relevant, focusing on its impact on supporting well-being. The Care Inspectorate Wales looks at the residential aspects of care in these cases, while Estyn assesses the educational side of things. Additionally, inspections evaluate linked children's homes, which can be another room in the same house or located a number of miles away.&#10;4. Shortcomings in independent schools have been identified, such as insufficient awareness of guidance and support for referring pupils to child and adolescent mental health services when needed. Estyn aims to address these concerns through their inspection guidance and the development of resources like the one created by Claire Morgan, which focuses on establishing a culture of improvement and reflection within schools.&#10;5. Pupil confidence in their school's ability to help them with their emotional and mental well-being is generally higher in primary schools than secondary schools. Factors contributing to this difference include pupils facing more challenges in adolescence, as well as potential gaps in support during the transition between primary and secondary education." target=" pick up on that as well. Just to explain how we work with independent schools, initially, to give the context. So, there are different kinds of independent schools. So, some have boarding provision, and where they have boarding provision, Care Inspectorate Wales would look at the boarding side of it, we'd look at the educational side of it. There are others where they may have a linked children's home, which can be another room in the same house, or it can be a number of miles away, and similarly there CIW would look at the residential aspects of the care and we'd look at the school. So, I think, there's a focus in the independent school standards regulations, which is a minimum that all schools have to meet to maintain a registration. There is a focus in that on how that school looks after and cares for its pupils, and there are focuses on that element of boarding provision where relevant, and the national minimum standards that the care inspectorate look at that have aspects around supporting well-being as well. What we do find in our inspections is that, overall, we generally find that pupils' well-being develops, they make good progress, and that care, support and guidance that schools give is good. What we mean by">
