    <edge source="Meilyr Rowlands views the new curriculum as an opportunity to significantly improve the quality of teaching and learning within schools. He believes that school leaders should use additional funding to prepare for the new curriculum by freeing up teachers to think about what it means for their own teaching practices. This process allows teachers to be more creative in their approaches, which can make teaching a more attractive profession and help retain talented educators. Rowlands suggests that schools need time to thoughtfully consider and implement the new curriculum, emphasizing its potential as a catalyst for positive change in education in Wales." target="Meilyr Rowlands expresses concern about the current situation regarding secondary schools in Wales, acknowledging that there are challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole. He is worried that half of Welsh children face uncertain prospects of attending a good or better secondary school, with over 10% of schools failing and 12% under Estyn review.&#10;&#10;However, Meilyr Rowlands also highlights positive aspects of the education system in Wales, mentioning the primary sector, special sector, and post-16 as sectors that are doing well. He sees the new curriculum as an opportunity to significantly improve the quality of teaching and learning within schools, believing that school leaders should use additional funding to prepare for the new curriculum by freeing up teachers to think about what it means for their own teaching practices.&#10;&#10;In summary, Meilyr Rowlands is both concerned about the current state of secondary education in Wales and appreciative of the positive aspects found in other sectors of the Welsh education system.">
