    <edge source="Yes, there is a correlation between a lack of support at a higher level and difficulties experienced by some authorities in providing quality education. Meilyr Rowlands, the Chief Inspector of Schools for Estyn, mentioned that out of the nine inspected local authorities so far in the current cycle, three have been identified as causing concern: Pembrokeshire, Powys, and Wrexham. He also noted that a common factor in these inspections is secondary schools, suggesting challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole.&#10;&#10;When discussing ERW, one of the regions including south-west and mid Wales, Meilyr Rowlands acknowledged that the lack of support at that level might be the reason why some authorities are suffering difficulties. This is especially relevant for two of the inspected authorities in this region.&#10;&#10;The dispute at higher levels may indirectly affect children by impacting the quality of education provided in these local authorities. The concerns about a lack of local capacity to support schools and the absence of collective capacity centrally contribute to the challenges faced by these authorities." target="1. A visit is planned to all authorities under ERW's jurisdiction, including regions in south-west and mid Wales, to assess their school improvement services. This visit aims to ensure that appropriate plans are in place for school improvement services and to survey schools about the support they receive from their authority or central teams in ERW.&#10;   &#10;2. The purpose of this visit is to gauge any potential disadvantages or impacts on schools firsthand, as well as to make sure that ERW has a plan for an appropriate school improvement service going forward. This proactive measure will help identify areas where support is needed and allow for the implementation of measures to improve educational quality.&#10;&#10;3. There is a joint committee meeting scheduled for March 19th, after which more information is expected regarding ERW's plans to manage their collective set of services. Stakeholders hope to gain clarity on how ERW will proceed in managing and delivering school improvement services to address the current concerns and challenges.&#10;&#10;4. A detailed link visit will be conducted to understand how ERW authorities are mitigating risks arising from recent developments, such as staff departures and lack of support at higher levels. This follow-up visit will help evaluate the effectiveness of existing measures and identify areas for improvement in school improvement services.">
