    <edge source="Yes, there is a correlation between a lack of support at a higher level and difficulties experienced by some authorities in providing quality education. Meilyr Rowlands, the Chief Inspector of Schools for Estyn, mentioned that out of the nine inspected local authorities so far in the current cycle, three have been identified as causing concern: Pembrokeshire, Powys, and Wrexham. He also noted that a common factor in these inspections is secondary schools, suggesting challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole.&#10;&#10;When discussing ERW, one of the regions including south-west and mid Wales, Meilyr Rowlands acknowledged that the lack of support at that level might be the reason why some authorities are suffering difficulties. This is especially relevant for two of the inspected authorities in this region.&#10;&#10;The dispute at higher levels may indirectly affect children by impacting the quality of education provided in these local authorities. The concerns about a lack of local capacity to support schools and the absence of collective capacity centrally contribute to the challenges faced by these authorities." target="1. Regional Consortia Inspections: The cycle of inspections for regional consortia is not explicitly mentioned in the transcripts; however, it is stated that the work of consortia regarding supporting curriculum reform will be looked at specifically over the next year. The robustness of these inspections and their coverage areas are also not detailed.&#10;&#10;2. Support from External Agencies: Over the past three years, external agencies have generally improved in their support for schools causing concern, particularly in terms of literacy and numeracy. Schools' knowledge of individual institutions' strengths and weaknesses has been utilized better to support and challenge these schools. However, there is still room for improvement in supporting schools in developing digital competence.&#10;&#10;3. Support for Literacy: Literacy remains a top priority for Estyn, and it has seen improvements over the years due to consistent prioritization. However, there are still concerns about boys' reading and literacy skills, with Wales consistently ranking low in Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA) ratings for reading.&#10;&#10;4. Challenges in Secondary Schools: There is a common factor of secondary schools struggling in inspections across several local authorities, which suggests challenges in this area for both individual authorities and the education system as a whole. Two inspected authorities in ERW's region (South-west and Mid Wales) might be experiencing difficulties due to a lack of support at that level.&#10;&#10;5. Impact on Quality of Education: The dispute at higher levels may indirectly affect children by impacting the quality of education provided in local authorities. Concerns about a lack of local capacity to support schools and the absence of collective capacity centrally contribute to the challenges faced by these authorities.">
