    <edge source="Yes, there is a correlation between a lack of support at a higher level and difficulties experienced by some authorities in providing quality education. Meilyr Rowlands, the Chief Inspector of Schools for Estyn, mentioned that out of the nine inspected local authorities so far in the current cycle, three have been identified as causing concern: Pembrokeshire, Powys, and Wrexham. He also noted that a common factor in these inspections is secondary schools, suggesting challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole.&#10;&#10;When discussing ERW, one of the regions including south-west and mid Wales, Meilyr Rowlands acknowledged that the lack of support at that level might be the reason why some authorities are suffering difficulties. This is especially relevant for two of the inspected authorities in this region.&#10;&#10;The dispute at higher levels may indirectly affect children by impacting the quality of education provided in these local authorities. The concerns about a lack of local capacity to support schools and the absence of collective capacity centrally contribute to the challenges faced by these authorities." target="Meilyr Rowlands expresses concern about the current situation regarding secondary schools in Wales, acknowledging that there are challenges in this area for several local authorities and the system as a whole. He is worried that half of Welsh children face uncertain prospects of attending a good or better secondary school, with over 10% of schools failing and 12% under Estyn review.&#10;&#10;However, Meilyr Rowlands also highlights positive aspects of the education system in Wales, mentioning the primary sector, special sector, and post-16 as sectors that are doing well. He sees the new curriculum as an opportunity to significantly improve the quality of teaching and learning within schools, believing that school leaders should use additional funding to prepare for the new curriculum by freeing up teachers to think about what it means for their own teaching practices.&#10;&#10;In summary, Meilyr Rowlands is both concerned about the current state of secondary education in Wales and appreciative of the positive aspects found in other sectors of the Welsh education system.">
