    <edge source="The agreed approach for inspecting and reporting on how regional consortia support curriculum reform over the next few years is through a thematic approach. Estyn, the education and training inspectorate for Wales, will look specifically at how each consortium is supporting curriculum reform in their local authorities as part of their local authority inspections. This will be reported on, but it won't be the same as doing an inspection of the consortia's work at this time. Estyn has discussed with the Welsh Government the possibility of adapting inspection to look specifically at regional consortia if they become statutory entities in the future. Estyn is currently negotiating with the Welsh Government to be able to inspect local authorities and regions at the same time, which would allow for a more comprehensive evaluation of the support provided by regional consortia." target="&#10;Content: So, what is the cycle of inspections for regional consortia, and how robust are those inspections? What areas do you cover?&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Well, regional consortia aren't actually statutory entities at the moment, and we don't have specific inspection powers relating to regional consortia. What we have are powers to inspect school improvement. So, on each of our local authority inspections, there will be, usually, an area that we're looking at that relates to school improvement, and that would involve us looking at the work of the consortia that the local authority has commissioned. What we've agreed with Welsh Government is that, over the next few years, we will take a thematic approach. So, the first area that we've said is that we'll look specifically at how each of them is supporting curriculum reform, and report on that. So, that will report specifically on the different ones, but it wouldn't be the same as doing an inspection of their work at this time.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Should they be on a statutory footing?&#10;Speaker: Jassa Scott&#10;Content: Well, I think that's something to be discussed">
